### Building a Simple Interactive Application

Let’s build a simple **To-Do List** application to put these concepts into practice. This app will allow users to add tasks to a list and mark them as completed.

#### Step 1: Set Up the Project

Use either Create React App or Vite to set up your project. Navigate to the project directory and start the development server.

#### Step 2: Create the To-Do List Component

We’ll create a `TodoList` component that manages the state of the to-do items and a `TodoItem` component to display each item.

##### `TodoItem.js`

```jsx
function TodoItem({ text, completed, onToggle }) {
  return (
    <li
      style={{ textDecoration: completed ? 'line-through' : 'none' }}
      onClick={onToggle}
    >
      {text}
    </li>
  );
}
```

This component:
- Takes `text`, `completed`, and `onToggle` as props.
- Displays the `text` of the to-do item.
- Strikes through the text if `completed` is `true`.
- Calls `onToggle` when clicked to toggle the completion status.

##### `TodoList.js`

```jsx
import { useState } from 'react';
import TodoItem from './TodoItem';

function TodoList() {
  const [todos, setTodos] = useState([
    { id: 1, text: 'Learn React', completed: false },
    { id: 2, text: 'Build a project', completed: false },
  ]);
  const [inputValue, setInputValue] = useState('');

  const handleInputChange = (e) => {
    setInputValue(e.target.value);
  };

  const handleAddTodo = () => {
    if (inputValue.trim() === '') return;
    setTodos([
      ...todos,
      { id: Date.now(), text: inputValue, completed: false },
    ]);
    setInputValue('');
  };

  const handleToggleTodo = (id) => {
    setTodos(
      todos.map((todo) =>
        todo.id === id ? { ...todo, completed: !todo.completed } : todo
      )
    );
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>To-Do List</h1>
      <input
        type="text"
        value={inputValue}
        onChange={handleInputChange}
        placeholder="Add a new task"
      />
      <button onClick={handleAddTodo}>Add</button>
      <ul>
        {todos.map((todo) => (
          <TodoItem
            key={todo.id}
            text={todo.text}
            completed={todo.completed}
            onToggle={() => handleToggleTodo(todo.id)}
          />
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}
```

This component:
- Manages the state of the to-do items using the `todos` state variable.
- Uses the `useState` hook to manage the `inputValue` for the input field.
- Provides functions to handle input changes (`handleInputChange`), adding a new to-do (`handleAddTodo`), and toggling the completion status (`handleToggleTodo`).
- Renders an input field, a button, and a list of `TodoItem` components.

#### Step 3: Render the `TodoList` Component

Update the `App.js` file to render the `TodoList` component.

```jsx
import TodoList from './TodoList';

function App() {
  return (
    <div className="App">
      <TodoList />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

#### Step 4: Test the Application

Start your development server and open your browser to test the application. You should be able to:
- Add new tasks by typing in the input field and clicking the "Add" button.
- Mark tasks as completed by clicking on them.
- See the tasks strike through when completed.

